Text.Value: No doubt the Old Mage will have much to say about your adventures, and you will have much to tell him.
*What happens next will be by your design, and yours alone.*
I'm not ready. It isn't fair.
I must seek Elminster's counsel - I must find a way to stabilise the orb for good.
No it isn't.
*Whatever time is left is yours and yours alone.*
Perhaps Mystra will even see fit to forgive you for making such a choice, and cure you of the orb.
If you do intend to stay in the city, the Undercellar may offer a suitable refuge while you learn how to hide in plain sight, as I once did.
We should stay in the city. Help to rebuild it.
We should stay in the city. Help to rebuild it.
For what it's worth, I think you are much improved now.
Me too.
I will reforge the Crown and become a god.
I will reforge the Crown and become a god.
You have my word.
I never trusted you - you were just my best chance of survival.
I wish you well, Gale of Waterdeep, for the fate of our world will depend on their failure to find you, or your success in defeating them when they do.
I will do what I have always done. I will survive.
I will deliver the Crown to Mystra, to ensure that none may access such power again.
I will deliver the Crown to Mystra, to ensure that none may access such power again.
But I would not recommend it. The city does not welcome the likes of us, at least not on its surface.
The expansion of one's mind with the intellect of others' is never a bad idea.
Embrace your evolution. You are more than you've ever been. All that has changed in you has changed for the better.
You can, if you wish.
You have become... important to me.
But I will not be joining you. The city has no love for the likes of me.
Very well. Then I bid you farewell. And... good luck.
Then for your sake I hope she shows you mercy. Or that you do to her.
You did well.
It's time I return to my books - they've been piling up, unread for too long.
I'm sorry.
They're lost to the Chionthar, with the Crown. Neither you nor anyone else will ever wield them again.
Our achievements must not be lost to posterity. I shall write this tale that all may learn from it.
May your path ahead lead you to the allies you desire.
I see.
Let's get out of this godsforsaken city. How about the Underdark?
Let's get out of this godsforsaken city. I hear Amn is lovely this time of year.
A word of advice - keep the stones close to you. For as we have seen, even a Netherbrain can be dominated.
You've earned a triumphant homecoming. Though you may find your instincts are somewhat changed - and people will treat you... unkindly.
I'll leave the Crown where it is. So long as it's separated from the stones, no one will ever wield its power again.
I'll leave the Crown where it is. So long as it's separated from the stones, no one will ever wield its power again.
I wish you well in this.
But I will not be joining you.
You trusted me.
I saved the world. The sacrifice was worth it.
I saved the world. The sacrifice was worth it.
Then this is where we part ways?
Then this is where we part ways?
I may not be able to read your thoughts anymore, but I'm certain I know them -
*But the orb is not your only concern.*
I must confess, I admire your ambition almost as much as I fear its consequences.
So what will you do now, Gale of Waterdeep?
I feel more powerful than ever.
Never mind a fledgling god.
But it matters not. We succeeded.
I really thought at this point that you might have let go of that...
You made your own choices. I merely nudged you in the direction that would result in our greatest chance of success.
The githyanki are leaving.
First? A very long nap.
I'll miss you, you know.
Not a bad idea - it will certainly be safer than staying in the city.
I'll miss you, too.
*Your prince has been sacrificed, and you have been abandoned by your queen.*
I can hear your thoughts.
Strange, isn't it? To have travelled this far, inseparable from one another, only to cut the cord at the final step.
*One last look to remember. One last look to say goodbye.*
I will deliver the Crown to Mystra - it will be safer in her hands than in the hands of mortals.
I will deliver the Crown to Mystra - it will be safer in her hands than in the hands of mortals.
We wouldn't have succeeded without your guidance.
We wouldn't have succeeded without your guidance.
I'm still angry that you manipulated me.
I'm not sure. This is all very new.
I was impressed. And - grateful.
*The orb pulses within you still - Elminster's magic is all that keeps it contained. As long as the magic remains, so do you.*
Return to the city. My home.
Battle forms comrades of the coldest souls, but it seems that yours is determined to stay frozen.
What will you do? Now that you have a life of your own to live?
What will you do now?
What will you do?
What will you do?
*Your prince has been sacrificed, and you have failed your queen.*
*The threat of the Grand Design is over, but your people will never accept you back into their embrace.*
Then keep the stones close. There will be those who seek to take them from you. To stake their claim on power, even though you do not.
You hold her opinion above mine still? In spite of all she's done to you?
The Netherstones, you have them.
*You are a mind flayer, the very thing you were taught to hate. Whatever self you still possess is quickly ebbing away.*
*You are a mind flayer, the very thing you sought to eradicate. Whatever self you still possess is quickly ebbing away.*
Oh. Your heart...
You're wondering what became of the Netherstones.
I'm glad you think so.
That's between me and Mystra.
That's between me and Mystra.
Live a good life, will you? Make it worthwhile.
And should our paths ever cross again, I will be glad to see you.
No doubt you will use them to summon the Crown. But what then? What will you do when such power is in your grasp?
And that is why we succeeded.
I did what I had to do.
I did what I had to do.
There are so many worlds I'm yet to see, and not much time to see them. I feel my next adventure calling.
This is my city. It needs authority.
It's a shame - with an attitude like that, you would have made a wonderful illithid.
*One last threshold to cross.*
I did. Completely.
A wise decision, and a humble one.
I'll miss you.
I'll miss you, mind flayer.
I trust you will enjoy the process, for few will believe the stories you have to tell.
I think it's time we part ways.
I think it's time we part ways.
Well-deserved. You will find your dreams much changed, full of colours and shapes you do not yet recognise. But you will know them, in time.
